org.multigraph
Class Data

java.lang.Object
  org.multigraph.Data

public abstract class Data
extends java.lang.Object

This is the (abstract) superclass for classes that Multigraph uses for loading, storing, and managing data to be plotted. When drawing a plot, Multigraph accesses the data through the methods of this class. Individual subclasses implement their own ways of loading and managing data.

Regardless of the details of the underlying data retrieval and/or storage implementation, all Data objects share a common abstract model for accessing their data. The model is based on the concept of sequences of data rows, such as in a spreadsheet or table. Each row contains a set of DataValues, and within a single Data object, all rows must have exactly the same number of values, or columns. The first value in the row is referred to as column 0, the next value as column 1, and so on.

A Data object also stores metadata about its columns --- an id (which is just a String) and a data type (DataValue.Type constant) for each column.

Broadly speaking, there are two kinds of concrete subclasses of the Data class, depending on how the class obtains its data. A "Static Data" class obtains all its data at once, when it is initialized, whereas a "Dynamic Data" class obtains its data on the fly, as it is needed. Dynamic Data classes might work asynchronously: a request to access a certain range of data might not immediately return all the data in that range --- it might result in an asynchronous request being generated to fetch data, and then a call to a Data.ReadyHandler object's dataReady() method being made once the response to the request has been received and processed.

getIterator

public Data.Iterator getIterator(java.lang.String[] columnIds,
                                 DataValue min,
                                 DataValue max,
                                 int buffer)
Return a Data.Iterator object for iterating over a sequence of rows in this Data object.

Specifically, the iterator should return an array containing the requested columns' values for all rows in this Data object for which the column 0 value is greater than or equal to min, and less than or equal to max. Furthermore, if buffer is nonzero, the iterator should return data from buffer additional rows outside each end of the range.

For example, if this Data object contains the following rows 

       6.5,23,42
       7.0,92,93
       7.5,45,38
       8.0,63,87
       8.5,54,42
       9.0,47,94
       9.5,44,65
and getIterator is called with min=7.5, max=8.5, and buffer=1, then the returned iterator should step through the following 5 rows (the ones where column 0 is between 7.5 and 8.5, inclusive, plus one additional one before and after that range): 
       7.0,92,93
       7.5,45,38
       8.0,63,87
       8.5,54,42
       9.0,47,94
The columnIds array determines which columns are actually returned by the iterator.

IMPORTANT NOTE: the rows in the Data object are always assumed to be sorted in increasing order of column 0, and this is always the column that is compared against min and max to determine which rows an interator should return. This is the case even if column 0 is not one of the ones listed in columnIds! Column 0 is special: it is the (only) column by which the data is ordered.

Parameters:
columnIds - the ids of the columns whose values should be returned by the iterator
min - the minimum DataValue in the desired range
max - the maximum DataValue in the desired range
buffer - number of extra values to include outside each end of the range

onReady

public void onReady(Data.ReadyHandler readyHandler)
Register a handler to be called when new data becomes available in this Data object. Static Data subclasses can ignore this method. Dynamic ones should override it with an implementation that stores the handler and arranges for it to be called when new data is available.

getBounds

public DataValue[] getBounds(java.lang.String columnId)
Return the upper and lower limit of a given column in this Data object. It is not yet at all clear what this function should do for dynamic (such as web service based) Data objects. Just ignore it for the moment.

Returns:
an array of two DataValues: [minimum, maximum]
